1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,750
Have you ever opened a document and seen garbled characters?

2
00:00:03,750 --> 00:00:07,200
For example, take a look at the sample Wikipedia article on the page here,

3
00:00:07,200 --> 00:00:09,390
and that's displayed with the wrong encoding.

4
00:00:09,390 --> 00:00:11,490
That happens when your text editor,

5
00:00:11,490 --> 00:00:14,715
browser or word processor is assuming the wrong encoding.

6
00:00:14,715 --> 00:00:18,630
You simply need to select the right encoding to display the document properly.

7
00:00:18,630 --> 00:00:21,110
Character sets and encodings are two things that

8
00:00:21,110 --> 00:00:24,830
every programmer needs to be aware of when working with any text data.

9
00:00:24,830 --> 00:00:27,590
A character set is a collection of characters,

10
00:00:27,590 --> 00:00:30,950
symbols, or glyphs used in writing and communication.

11
00:00:30,950 --> 00:00:33,980
It includes letters, digits, punctuation marks,

12
00:00:33,980 --> 00:00:38,455
and other special characters that are found in various languages and scripts.

13
00:00:38,455 --> 00:00:42,485
Encoding or a character encoding is a scheme that assigns

14
00:00:42,485 --> 00:00:47,945
a unique numeric identifier or code point to each character and a character set.

15
00:00:47,945 --> 00:00:52,145
These numeric identifiers are then represented in binary format,

16
00:00:52,145 --> 00:00:54,065
a sequence of zeros and ones,

17
00:00:54,065 --> 00:00:57,335
so that they can be stored and processed by computers.

18
00:00:57,335 --> 00:01:00,755
Different encodings can be used to represent the same character set,

19
00:01:00,755 --> 00:01:04,070
but they may assign different numeric identifiers to the characters.

20
00:01:04,070 --> 00:01:07,795
Here's a few examples of popular character sets and encoding schemes.

21
00:01:07,795 --> 00:01:12,395
ASCII is an older encoding scheme that handles symbols, letters, and digits,

22
00:01:12,395 --> 00:01:15,320
and contains 128 characters including letters,

23
00:01:15,320 --> 00:01:18,155
digits, punctuation, and control characters.

24
00:01:18,155 --> 00:01:22,400
For example, the capital A has an ASCII value of 65,

25
00:01:22,400 --> 00:01:25,930
while the digit 1 has an ASCII value of 49.

26
00:01:25,930 --> 00:01:29,720
Unicode is a comprehensive character encoding standard that aims to

27
00:01:29,720 --> 00:01:33,545
represent virtually all writing systems and characters used worldwide.

28
00:01:33,545 --> 00:01:36,560
It is used by most modern systems.

29
00:01:36,560 --> 00:01:39,830
Unicode covers not only letters, digits, and punctuation,

30
00:01:39,830 --> 00:01:41,165
but also special symbols,

31
00:01:41,165 --> 00:01:43,420
emojis and non-Latin scripts.

32
00:01:43,420 --> 00:01:47,135
Unicode Transformation Format eight bit or UTF-8,

33
00:01:47,135 --> 00:01:49,160
is a very popular encoding system.

34
00:01:49,160 --> 00:01:53,575
It can handle symbols from multiple languages and support a lot of unique characters.

35
00:01:53,575 --> 00:01:57,590
If you have a CSV file in UTF-8 format you can specify

36
00:01:57,590 --> 00:02:01,760
the encoding scheme directly when reading the file through the encoding parameter.

37
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:05,240
When you encode a string in Python say using ASCII,

38
00:02:05,240 --> 00:02:07,685
it turns the character string into a byte string,

39
00:02:07,685 --> 00:02:10,625
or in other words, a sequence of bytes that are machine-readable.

40
00:02:10,625 --> 00:02:15,410
The output of this would be a byte string as denoted by the b before the apostrophes.

41
00:02:15,410 --> 00:02:17,965
Why are we still able to see hello world though?

42
00:02:17,965 --> 00:02:22,505
Because Python 3 is automatically decoding the string from ASCII so we can read it.

43
00:02:22,505 --> 00:02:25,925
Regarding decoding, when you decode a string in Python,

44
00:02:25,925 --> 00:02:30,065
it turns from byte stream to a character string that is human-readable.

45
00:02:30,065 --> 00:02:32,840
Similar to encode, you can decode a byte string by

46
00:02:32,840 --> 00:02:36,005
using the decode function and specify the encoding scheme.

47
00:02:36,005 --> 00:02:38,270
Now you can see that the b is gone from

48
00:02:38,270 --> 00:02:41,170
the output and the output is just a string, hello world.

49
00:02:41,170 --> 00:02:46,175
When I say string, it's worth noting Python three has one text type called STR,

50
00:02:46,175 --> 00:02:47,965
which holds Unicode data.

51
00:02:47,965 --> 00:02:51,915
Python 3 also has to by types; bytes and bytearray.

52
00:02:51,915 --> 00:02:54,390
These objects are very similar however,

53
00:02:54,390 --> 00:02:55,740
have one key difference.

54
00:02:55,740 --> 00:02:57,785
A bytes object is immutable,

55
00:02:57,785 --> 00:02:59,885
which means that once it is created,

56
00:02:59,885 --> 00:03:01,255
it cannot be modified.

57
00:03:01,255 --> 00:03:03,000
A bytesarray is mutable.

58
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:05,910
Once you create it, you can modify it.

